Virtual Class Night
Brooke Walter

Class night is held every year in the auditorium at school and each senior gets recognized on stage and says what they’re doing after highschool. Each senior picks an underclassman to be their torch bearer, and the seniors line up around the auditorium and the torch bearers blow out the seniors' candles. The tradition is that after class night you go out to dinner with your torch bearer, but this year we had to do it over a zoom meeting. All of the seniors and some teachers were in the meeting, the class officers introduced the seniors and told where they’re going. Then the senior slideshow was shown. It was very short and sweet but it was nice to at least be recognized and get to see some of our classmates

post_text:
Have Crime Rates Dropped Since Covid Lockdown?
By Amanda Rosekrans

The first two months of this year crime rates in New York had been rising at a rapid speed. Now, with people being forced to stay home and social distance, it has dropped.
In New York City crime rates have dropped 28.5 percent in the month of April according to NYPD statistics. Certain crimes have skyrocketed since the lockdown, like burglaries to small businesses.
Politico New York states that in April 2020, there were 5,121 major felony crimes, compared to the 7,162 during the same month last year.
The real question is, now that things are starting to open back up, will this decrease in crime continue to fall?

post_text:
Justice For George Floyd

By Wisteria Kirk

George Floyd, an unarmed black man was killed Monday, May 25, 2020 in Minneapolis. Derek Chauvin, a police officer, pinned Floyd to the ground with his knee on Floyd’s neck. Chauvin continues to keep him pinned to the ground, despite protest from onlookers as well as Floyd stating, “Please, please, please, I can't breathe...My stomach hurts. My neck hurts. Please, please. I can't breathe." In a matter of minutes Floyd goes unconscious and is later pronounced dead.
All four Minneapolis police officers involved were arrested and one has been charged with third degree murder and second degree manslaughter.
The incident touched off protests in cities all over the United States over the weekend, some of them leading to violence. .

Guardian Reports U.S. Military Developing Game Changing Covid Test
By: Jared Howe

A new test, potentially capable of identifying COVID-19 in people before they become infectious has been designed by scientists working for the United States military, according to an exclusive report from the British based news organization, The Guardian.
The Guardian reports the blood-based test came from a project by the U.S. military’s Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) meant to quickly diagnose germ or chemical warfare poisoning, and was repurposed when the coronavirus pandemic occurred.

post_text:
Gas Prices Small Silver Lining to Covid Cloud

By Wisteria Kirk

COVID-19 is definitely a drag, but one perk is the low gas prices. This pandemic is causing a sharp decline in the demand for gas. Only essential workers have to drive to work everyday and others are following the advice to stay home.
The lower demand for gas coincided with the surplus in the oil market, which lowered prices per barrel and compounded the drop in prices at the pump.
Typically during the winter, gas prices are lower while during the summer they increase when there is high demand for summer driving activities.
At this time, according to AAA, the per gallon average across the United States is $1.85.
Kentucky is seen to have the lowest gas prices at the moment at a whopping 89 cents a gallon, followed by Ohio selling gas at 91 cents a gallon.
The last time gas prices were this low was in 2004, due to a crash in the oil market.
As states reopen and the nation starts to drive, prices will most likely start to rise. Drivers will probably still see lower prices over the summer months than last year.

post_text:
Experience Helps South Korea Flatten The Curve

By Alex Larsen

For the first time in months, South Korea announced on Thursday, April 30, that they had a full day without any new Coronavirus cases. Despite South Korea having a dense population, they have been able to contain and treat Coronavirus patients at a much better rate than the US.
South Korea reported their first Coronavirus case on January 20, just one day prior to the US' first case.
Their response to the virus has been much swifter and impactful than the U.S., helping them to curb the virus.
This is due to the outbreak of MERS (Middle East Respiratory Syndrome) just five years ago. Since then the South Korean government has been continuously upgrading and advancing their screening centers, contact tracing, emergency action plans, as well as other response measures.

By: Jared Howe
New guidance from the US military will bar individuals who have been hospitalized for COVID-19 from enlisting.
The guidance is contained in a military recruitment memo from US Military Entrance Processing Command (MEPCOM). It is circulating on social media and was first reported on by Military Times on Wednesday.
The memo states that a COVID-19 diagnosis, even after recovery, would be considered disqualifying.

post_text:
This Day in History - The Attack on Attu

By Zach Lattin

On this day in history, May 11, 1943, American troops staged a successful landing on the Alasskan island of Attu driving the Japanese forces off of the island.
Attu was invaded by Japanese forces a year before and put up multiple defenses on the island to slow the American army headed inland. The battle lasted for 19 days and saw 3829 casualties in the attack with 549 of them being killed in action.
The battle of Attu was the only land battle in World War II to be held on American soil.

post_text:
Closings amidst COVID-19

By Alex Larsen

Cayuga County has been hit relatively hard with Coronavirus, with at least 48 confirmed cases, and in response to this, many businesses and public offices have remained closed. Many town offices are closed to the public, such as Ledyard, Aurora, Sennett, and Flemming. Most, including Aurora and Fleming, will have the staff operating under shorter hours, or on alternating days. Ledyard’s staff will be available only over phone or e-mail, however Sennett will remain fully staffed.
All restaurants and bars are barred from having in-house dining, but many restaurants remain open for take-out, including The King Ferry Pizzeria, Dugan's Country Grill, and The Fargo.
Movie theaters, bowling alleys, barber shops and tattoo parlors are considered non-essential, and will remain closed until May 15 at the earliest.
Libraries and museums are also closed, with all the libraries in the Finger Lakes Library system being closed.

post_text:
Hand Sanitizer at the King Ferry Corner Store
By Isis Binns
Hand sanitizer has proven itself to be a very hot commodity in the midst of this pandemic, and it has been nearly impossible to find in any stores for months now.
However, the King Ferry Corner Store has brought hand sanitizer, and lots of it, close to home.
The Corner Store has a great abundance of liquid hand sanitizer that you can apply in a spray bottle. The sanitizer has been produced by Cayuga Ingredients and boasts an 80% alcohol content.
You can buy the sanitizer in a 4 oz glass spray bottle for $4 (+tax), and it can be refilled at the store for $1 (+tax).
You can also buy a quart container of the sanitizer to refill your own container, or the spray bottle, for $8 (+tax).
The store also has 7 oz containers of gel hand sanitizer available for $7.99 (+tax), but the quantity is very limited for that item.

post_text:
Coronavirus Surpasses Vietnam War Fatalities

By Jared Howe

An estimated 47,434 American soldiers were killed in battle during the Vietnam War, which spanned from 1964 to 1975. An additional 10,786 died in the theater of war, but out of battle, making a total of 58,220 deaths.
As of April 28, 2020 the death toll from Covid 19 has reached 58,365 US deaths. It’s been many decades since Americans died in this mass on U.S. soil. The last comparable historic death toll was the 1918 influenza pandemic, which killed 675,000 Americans.

Food Pantry Needs Donations
By Isis Binns

In this time of need across the country, the King Ferry Food Pantry is doing record business.
Families throughout our community are in need of non perishable foods to feed their families during this time of crisis, and the King Ferry Food Pantry is fund raising in an effort to make sure they can meet the growing needs. .
Any and all donations are welcome, but during this time there is an increasing need for shelf-stable protein sources. Examples include canned tuna/salmon, canned chicken/other meats, canned/dried beans, canned soups/stews, peanut butter, nuts, canned chili, trail mix,
The food pantry is located in the Agriculture Shop of the Southern Cayuga High School, (near the greenhouse in the high school parking lot).
The King Ferry Food Pantry is also able to take donations of money on their website,
kingferryfoodpantry.org.
There is also a donation box in the King Ferry Corner Store where you can drop off items, and they will be picked up by a representative from the King Ferry Food Pantry.

Schools throughout New York State will remain shuttered through the end of the school year, Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo announced Friday, confirming what educators, union leaders and Mayor Bill de Blasio had said was inevitable weeks earlier.

post_text:
Extended Stop Move Order Starting To Impact Military Finances

By: Jared Howe

The military is seeing an upswing in issues its families face regarding their quality of life and finances after the Defense Department extended its stop move order until June 30.
All DoD Service members stop movement, both internationally and domestically, while this memorandum is in effect.
All DoD civilian personnel , and dependents of DoD Service members and DoD civilian personnel, whose travel is government-funded, will stop movement, both internationally and domestically, while this memorandum is in effect.”

Initial problems from the original order, which started in March and was supposed to conclude in May, seemed to dissipate as the military services provided aid and families began to adjust. However, new data from the Blue Star Families Pain Points Survey shows a latent rise in military families paying for housing in two or more places and families losing childcare.

post_text:
Super Bowl Champ Joins Front Lines Of Coronavirus Fight As A Doctor

By: Jared Howe

Life was a whirlwind for Kansas City Chiefs player Laurent Duvernay-Tardif after his team beat the San Francisco 49ers in the Super Bowl. But life was soon going to become drastically different for the NFL player, who also happens to hold a doctorate in medicine.Duvernay-Tardif says he started to think about people who were going through tougher times — including the physicians he knew from medical school.Soon, the 29-year-old was starting to ask how he could help. Since he didn't yet have a license to practice medicine, he was using his platform to relay messages from health officials to his followers. Still, he wanted to do more.After discussing it with his girlfriend, who could be at risk of exposure to the virus if he began working with patients, Duvernay-Tardif decided to officially join the fight. He said his team has been "amazing" and was "proud" of his decision.

Kaley Driscoll Awarded For Her Academic and Athletic Achievements

By Amanda Rosekrans

SCCS senior Kaley Driscoll was awarded the New York State Athletic Administrators Association (NYSAAA) Chapter 4 Academic Student Award.

This award is presented annually to one female and one male student in Section IV who excel in both athletics and academics.

The students not only must meet the high academic standards to be considered for the award, they also were required to complete an essay on 'how athletics has influenced their drive for success'.

Among her other accomplishments Kaley played on the boys’ varsity soccer team this past fall because SCCS was unable to field a girls’ varsity team due to lack of enough players.

She was recognised at a luncheon on February 13, 2020 for her academic and athletic achievements.

NYS New Public Mask Law Due to Corona
By Lilly Colton

New York Governor Andrew Cuomo has ordered New Yorkers to wear face masks when they are outside their houses and social distancing is not possible. He has also ordered all essential workers to start wearing medical masks when they are at their job.
Employers are required to provide these workers masks at no cost to the worker.
A number of businesses, including Tops and Wegmans, will not allow customers to enter their store unless the customer is wearing a mask.

If any person wants to enter a store or public building they must wear a medical mask or cover their face in some way, otherwise they can be denied entry to the building.

Silas Warren-McCormick, Budding Businessman

By Alex Larsen

Silas Warren-McCormick, an eighth grader at Southern Cayuga is one of 15 students who are in the Young Entrepreneurs Academy.The Academy, sponsored by Cayuga Community College.
The Academy is a 30 week program in which the students are mentored as they create and run their own business or not-for-profits.
At the end of the program, the students will pitch their ideas to investors in a Shark Tank-esque formatl.
All 15 of these students are from schools in the Cayuga County area, but Silas and his idea are among the best there. Silas’s product, which is a battery bank powered by solar energy to charge handheld devices such as phones and tablets, has already sold 25 units to both CCC and Wells College, and is not his first venture into solar power.
When he was in seventh grade he adapted a tablet to be solar powered and presented it in a science fair. Silas enjoys the program very much, and despite the closure of schools and current situation with the Coronavirus, the students are still working on their business plans.

U.K Prime Minister in Intensive Care Following Hospital Visit

Mark Saxton

Science

Monday April 6, 2020, Boris Johnson - the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom - was moved into intensive care following a hospital visit from the day before.

Johnson is one of 52,000 people in the U.K to contract Covid-19 and one of the 1.3 million to contract Covid-19 worldwide.

Despite the Prime Minister’s visit to intensive care following a sharp decline in his condition Monday night, he is in “good spirits” and is currently in a stable condition, and breathing without assistance according to his spokesperson.

The United Kingdom’s Secretary of State for Foreign Commonwealth Affairs of the United Kingdom, Dominic Raab, is filling in for Boris Johnson as interim Prime Minister while Johnson recovers in the hospital.

Breaks and Pacing During Covid 19

By Wisteria Kirk

COVID-19 has been a stressful situation for everyone. On top of having to get adjusted to online school, we have been informed we will no longer be having spring break.
It is normal to be anxious in this unfortunate situation. If you are feeling stressed here are some fun ways to relax and have a day to focus on yourself.
Have a spa day! No matter who you are, everyone can have a spa day. Whether it’s doing little things to make you feel better like painting your nails or doing a facemask or even just taking a long bath or shower. Anything can help to de-stress.
Take a moment to yourself and a break from schoolwork. It is alway okay to give yourself a day to watch some Netflix and lay in bed. If you're not someone who likes to sit in bed all day, go for a run and de-stress through exercise.
Seeing a familiar face may also brighten your mood. Call or FaceTime a friend to catch up on their quarantine activities. You can refer to “Staying Social While Social Distancing” for more ideas to stay in touch with your friends!

Cancelled Break Not A Popular Decision
By Brooke Walter

When I read an article about the Governor saying highschool students will not have a spring break and will resume classes during that week I was confused and didn’t think it would apply to us so I didn’t really think about it. The workload is tiring and stressful especially when I have so many other things to think and worry about as I am a senior.

post_text:
MyPillow Starts Production of Face Masks

Mark Saxton

Science

The company famous for its television marketing and bedtime comfort - MyPillow - has begun to produce cotton face masks to help the fight against Covid-19.

MyPillow founder/CEO Mike Lindell announced Friday March 29, 2020 that 75 percent of his company’s factories would be reorganized to produce cotton face masks instead of pillows, and that his company retooled its factories in “three days.”

This comes just a few days after President Trump announced that he would be invoking the Defense Protection Act to make General Motors shift its focus from automobiles to face masks.

MyPillow CEO Mike Lindell has said that his company produces about 10,000 masks a day and hopes by Friday to produce over 50,000 masks.

MyPillow’s face masks will not be available for public consumption, but will be distributed to medical personnel and hospitals.

post_text:
The Corona Diaries

From a Senior’s Point of View
By Brooke Walter

I wanted to try and get feedback from some other seniors to hear what they think about not having school and doing online classes.
I talked to senior Rachel Richardson and here are some of her thoughts
“It's just sad that we are missing the so-called best part of highschool and we didn't even realize it before it happened. We have no control on how we can spend the last part of our highschool career. I just really wish I could've given everyone a hug before we left.”
Rachel isn't taking this lightly; she really misses school and everyone there.
Jon Heath said “I'm sad, I miss seeing the boys everyday, I get my homework done and then I don't know what to do because I can't leave the house. I feel like they upped our work somehow but for me it's easy. The only reason I want to go back to school is to see my teachers and friends, and I want to have graduation.”
I think this has been much harder on the seniors than other kids, it's just a hard time for us knowing we can't be there when it's almost the end.

The Corona Diaries-Loss of Professional And College Sports Sorely Missed.

By: Jared Howe

The National Basketball Association is going to be postponed until further notice due to the Coronavirus. A few players have been diagnosed with the virus and the Association doesn't want to further the spreading of COVID-19 to any other players or fans. Few NBA players such as Zion Williamson, Giannis Antetokounmpo and Blake Griffin have donated thousands of dollars in funds towards the employees missing out on pay as the season is suspended.

Not only are the NBA players upset about the abrupt stoppage of their season, the fans are too, especially the fans that love to play basketball. My friends and I can't go out and play basketball together because we have to be quarantined and can’t expose ourselves to each other.

The effect seems even more dramatic because this is a time when having sports to watch on TV would be a real help and distraction, but for now, whether your sport is basketball, baseball, hockey or lacrosse, watching it or playing it isn't an option.

post_text:
Local Businesses May Have What You Need

Full Disclosure- Isis Binns is an employee at the King Ferry Corner Store and has personally seen the inventory she write about.

By Isis Binns

The recent progression of COVID-19 in the area has affected every aspect of our small community. One part of the community that hasn’t taken a hit is local stores.
Big corporations like Walmart and Target may have lower prices, but they have been completely picked through and have almost nothing left to offer in terms of essential supplies.
Local, smaller stores are still well stocked with supplies like toilet paper, cleaning supplies, and nonperishable food items.
Prices are definitely a little steeper at these smaller businesses, but money spent there is supporting local people in the community and helping our local economy.
Smaller stores are also still getting shipments of grocery items that are out of stock nearly everywhere else, so checking these stores for supplies is definitely worth your time.

On This Day in History - The First Spacewalk
By Zach Lattin

On this day in history March 18, 1965, Russian Cosmonaut Alexei Leonov succeeded at the first spacewalk after exiting the Voskhod 2 space capsule while orbiting the Earth.
Alexei was an U.S.S.R. Air Force major with over 278 hours of flight time and had completed 115 parachute jumps. He was selected to be interviewed for the cosmonaut training program for his parachuting background, as the shuttles envisioned at that time would not be landing and they would have to eject out of them.
While recounting the event with a British news agency, Alexei stated "It was so quiet I could even hear my heart beat, I was surrounded by stars and was floating without much control. I will never forget the moment. I also felt an incredible sense of responsibility."

Tree Project Hosting Pizza And A Movie

By Amanda Rosekrans

The Southern Cayuga Anne Frank Tree Project will be sponsoring their annual pizza and movie night March 27, 2020 in the SCCS auditorium.
The Long Walk Home is about a woman named Odessa Cotter (played by Whoopi Goldberg) who works as a housekeeper and ends up boycotting the bus by walking 9 miles to work. The woman she works for, Miriam Thompson (played by Sissy Spacek) offered her a ride which defied her husbands racist views and the town council. Odessa and Miriam find a respect for each other and create a friendship that is difficult in a world of black vs. white.
Pizza will be served at 6:00 p.m. in the SCCS High School cafeteria, followed by the movie in the high school auditorium.
Admission to both dinner and the movie are free and open to students and community members alike.

Dumb Crooks- Saved By the Brick- Criminal Candidate For Concussion Protocal

By Amario May

Sometimes events conspire to send you the message that you’ve chosen the wrong line of work.
In Suitland, Maryland, the police began looking for a burglar who they dubbed the “Bad Luck Bandit”. The nickname resulted from the unidentified man’s attempt to break into a restaurant by throwing a brick through the business’s window.
The Prince George's County Police Department had caught a man on a surveillance video, trying to break a window protecting the restaurant’s front counter. The first two attempts were unsuccessful, with the brick failing to break the window. On the third try, the brick bounced off the window back and hit him in the head.
The video showed the would- be burglar falling down, and laying on the ground for a few minutes before getting up and leaving.
text:
Dumb Crooks- Saved By the Brick- Criminal Candidate For Concussion Protocal

By Amario May

Sometimes events conspire to send you the message that you’ve chosen the wrong line of work.
In Suitland, Maryland, the police began looking for a burglar who they dubbed the “Bad Luck Bandit”. The nickname resulted from the unidentified man’s attempt to break into a restaurant by throwing a brick through the business’s window.
The Prince George's County Police Department had caught a man on a surveillance video, trying to break a window protecting the restaurant’s front counter. The first two attempts were unsuccessful, with the brick failing to break the window. On the third try, the brick bounced off the window back and hit him in the head.
The video showed the would- be burglar falling down, and laying on the ground for a few minutes before getting up and leaving.

Money Can Buy Happiness If You Use It Right

By Amario May

Although its common belief that money cannot buy happiness, Rachel Lapierre is proving otherwise by giving all her money away.
Lapierre is a 55-year-old former beauty queen from Quebec who won the Gagnant Lifetime Lottery in 2013, which means that she receives a $1,000 stipend every week and she’s going to keep receiving the payments for the rest of her life.
Instead of using her money for lavish possessions, she uses it to run a charity and to help the less fortunate. Lapierre tells BBC’s “ Money Is money, when you’re born you don’t have anything, and when you go, you go with nothing but your memories. You go with what you did here in life.”
Lapierre says she does this to promote good deeds, and good deeds could be anything big or small. Happiness comes from the heart, not from materialistic items.

post_text:
Now You Know-The Rubik’s Cube has 43 Quintillion Combinations

Mark Saxton

With a total of six different colored faces and 9 individual squares on each face, the popular 1980’s toy the Rubik’s Cube has a total of 43,252,003,274,489,856,000 possible permutations.

If someone were to have one dollar for each possible combination you could spend one trillion dollars each day for every day for the next 118 thousand years.

This also means that if you could turn the Rubik’s Cube into a new configuration once every second it would take you 1.4 trillion years to find each unique configuration of the cube. It is estimated that the universe is 14 billion years old, meaning if you started at the same time the Big Bang happened, you wouldn’t even be halfway finished.

If you stacked a rubik’s cube with each unique combination end to end they would be 261 light years long.

Now you know

Kirk Again Takes Gold And Silver For Photos

By Amanda Rosekrans
SCCS junior Wisteria Kirk received two gold keys, two silver keys, and two honorable mentions for six photos that she submitted to the CNY Scholastic Art Awards.
The art work was on display at Onondaga Community College from January 21- March 1, 2020.
Thousands of students in central New York submitted their best artwork and hundreds of them received awards and honorable mentions.
The awards program is sponsored M&T Bank and the work is exhibited at Onondaga Community College.
A special awards ceremony took place on Tuesday, January 21, 2020. It featured Gold Key (first place) selections, which qualifies the work for national competition. The ceremony also presented local awards, cash prizes, and special recognition.
This is Kirk’s fourth consecutive year being recognised in this art event. She has been pursuing photography since seventh grade, submitted ten photos to the annual art event and in previous years she has won eight gold, seven silver, and nine honorable mentions.

This Day in History - The Division of Europe
By Zach lattin

On this day in history, March 5, 1946, Winston Churchill, the former Prime Minister of Britain, said to a crowd in Fulton, Missouri, that “an iron curtain has descended on the continent [of Europe].”
This was said after the conclusion of World War Two in Europe since the countries the Soviet Union “freed” were set up as communist satellite states splitting the continent in half between a democratic west, and a communist east.
War torn Europe was split at the Yalta Conference, held on the Crimean peninsula in February of 1945. As the defeat of Germany became evident, the Allies (U.S.A., Great Britain and U.S.S.R.) met to devise a post war plan for Europe. Winston Churchhill was against the idea of giving Stalin all of eastern Europe, but with the war still going on in the Pacific, the Soviets accepted no other terms, and Franklin D. Roosevelt “trusting” Stalin to give them free and fair elections, conceded..

Catch Him If You Can

By Amario May

Another criminal, on the run from law enforcement, took an unwise approach of taunting local Gwent Police when they posted a Facebook appeal to trace him.
Logan James, at the time 19 and from Caerphilly, Wales, was wanted for breaching his prison release terms after serving his sentence for wounding, affray, common assault and being in possession of a knife.
“Haha catch me if you can, won't see me slipping” James taunted via his Facebook page. James later told a news agency that he posted the taunt after he concluded the police weren't trying too hard to find him, because he had been walking around his home in plain sight and the police never discovered his whereabouts.
Later that day, James was caught and the police, who saw his
Facebook post and thanked him for drawing attention to their efforts to return him to prison.

This Day In History - Star Spangled Banner

By Zach Lattin

On this day in history, March 3, 1931, President Herbert Hoover signed the bill that made Francis Scott Key’s Star Spangled Banner the national anthem.
Francis Scott Key wrote the poem that was originally called The Defense of Fort McHenry while being held prisoner on a british ship watching the bombardment of the Maryland fort during the war of 1812 but was later renamed to The Star Spangled Banner which we know it as now.
John Stafford Smith and Jamie Salisbury composed the music that went along with the poem.

On This Day in History - The Rise to Power
By Zach Lattin

On this day in history, February 27, 1933, the building that housed the German government, the Reichstag, mysteriously burned down and arson was suspected.
Hitler and his Nazi party blamed the German communist party for the act, and used the fire as an excuse to impose martial law inside of Germany, further increasing their political power on the divided populace of the nation.
Hitler also used the fire as an excuse to restrict civil rights in Germany.
Though the Nazis blamed the communists for the fire it has been suspected that Hitler and the Nazis themselves started it for the above reasons of gaining power in Germany.

On This Day in History - A Legend is Born
By Zach Lattin

On this day in history, February 25, 1836 Samuel Colt patented the first revolving cylinder multi shot firearm or revolver for short in the United States.
The firearm would become a staple of the American “cowboys” and settling of the western states of America. The firearm, paired alongside the Henry repeating rifle, would be considered the guns that won the west and cementing their places in firearm history.
As a teenager and a seaman colt dreamed of having a revolving pistol capable of firing multiple times before reloading and went to work on creating his piece. In 1835 the French and British Patented the revolver in their countries and in America the year after.

Dumb Criminals- Alcohol And Flightless Birds Poor Mix
By Amario May

Two Welsh tourists landed themselves in court in 2012 after getting drunk and stealing a penguin named Dirk from Sea World in Australia.
Rhys Owen Jones and Keri Mules, from South Wales, broke into the a Queensland Gold Coasts park and swam with the dolphins, let off a fire extinguisher in a shark habitat, and stole a penguin named Dirk.
When they had woke up, they had tried their incompetent best to care for the flightless animal by keeping him in the bathroom, and trying to feed him, the court heard.
After trying their best to take care of the penguin, Jones and Mules had released the penguin into a canal with locals witnessing and calling the police.
Both were fined 1,000 Australian dollars which is equivalent to about $660 in the United States, and were told to drink a little less vodka.
Dirk was returned to the zoo unharmed.

Artists Invited to Sculpt a Monument for Roswell, New Mexico

Mark Saxton

The city of Roswell, New Mexico - home of the famous U.F.O crash in 1947 - is looking for artists to design a city monument using a decommissioned piece of playground equipment originally installed in the 1960’s, making it over 50 years old.

The city wants the monument to honor not only the popular conspiracy theory but also the father of modern rocket science, Robert H. Goddard - who did much of his work in Roswell between 1930-41, and the sci-fi pop-culture that has swept through the city since the 40’s. The location of the monument has not yet been chosen and will be up to the artist’s discretion

The only requirement from the city is that artists must use the original rocket-ship design as the old playground equipment, but other than the rocket-ship they may do anything they wish.

The competition started on January 24, 2020 and all designs are due to the city on February 28, 2020. The city will then choose the artist or team of artists to design the city’s new monument.

post_text:
This Day in History - Remember The Alamo

By Zach Lattin

On this day in history, February 12, 1836, Mexican army General Santa Anna crossed the Rio Grande river headed to the Texas Alamo.
The battle of the Alamo would start on February 23 with the Mexican army winning the battle and killing all of the Texan fighters inside of the fort.
This sparked a fighting spirit inside of the Texans with Sam Houston leading forces to San Jacinto, winning a quick, yet decisive battle, and gained independence for Texas.
Among the historical figures killed at the Alamo were Colonel Williams B. Travis, James Bowie, and the frontiersman Davy Crockett.
The battles established the Texas Republic with Sam Houston as its president.

post_text:
This Day in History - The Big Con
By Zach lattin

On this day in history, February 10, 1915, president Woodrow Wilson blasted the British for using the American flag on their merchant ships to avoid German submarines.
The Germans implemented a type of naval combat called unrestricted submarine warfare, in which they declared that ships found headed to Britain or France shall be sunk to try and starve out their enemies since their main resources came from overseas.
Since the Germans decided to use the submarine warfare on what they deemed “enemy ships” the British decided to fly the American flag in hopes the Germans would not attack them for being neutral and not wanting the Americans to join the war.

post_text:
This Day in History - The Beginning of The End
By Zach Lattin

On this day in history, February 4, 1945, the big three leaders, Franklin D. Roosevelt(United States) , Winston Churchill(Great Britain), and Joseph Stalin (Soviet Union) met in Yalta, Ukraine, to discuss the division of Europe after the war and how governments should be set up in the freed countries.

In the Yalta Conference, the three leaders discussed the unconditional surrender of Germany, splitting it into four zones controlled by the U.S., Great Britain, France, and the Soviets. The same would be done with the capital city of Berlin but only between the U.S. and Soviet Union.

The leaders of democracies also, in very poor judgment, left Eastern Europe to be dealt with by the Soviets who set up a series of puppet states splitting Europe into a western democracy, and an the east into communist satellite states with Winston Churchill famously saying, “From Stettin in the Baltic to Trieste in the Adriatic, an iron curtain has descended across the continent”

An Unsuspecting Man, and A Suspected Arrest

By Amario May

Officials were left perplexed after an Afghan Taliban commander, who turned himself in, tried to claim the $100 reward for his capture.
Mohammad Ashan, a “mid-to-low-level Taliban commander,'' was suspected of organizing attacks on the U.S. and Afghan troops in the east of his country. According to reports, Ashan had walked up to a police checkpoint and asked for the $100 reward.
The Authorities were taken aback by this act of stupidity, and didn't have any words to explain his actions, but one U.S. official reportedly told journalists, “Clearly, this man is an imbecile.”

This Day in History - California Gold Rush
By Zach Lattin

On this day in history, January 30, 1848, miner John Marshall found the first gold nugget in Coloma, California, kicking off the gold rush with more than half a million people going to California to find gold.
More than 750,000 pounds of gold was excavated in the seven year period the rush was going on, and the largest single piece of gold weighed 109.2 pounds and was found at the Sierra Buttes Mine Property.

To sign up for the SAT you will need to go to the guidance office and talk with Paula Schmitt and write your name on the sign-up sheet.
If you are a junior that has never taken the SAT, the cost is covered by the school. If this is your second time taking the SAT the cost will be $47.50 without the essay portion, and $64.50 with the essay portion.
Mrs. Schmitt said It is important so sign up as soon as possible, to reduce the scramble of preparing paperwork.

post_text:
This Day in History- Shuttle Tragedy Claimed Seven Lives
By Zach Lattin

On this day in history, January 28, 1986 the Challenger space shuttle was set to lift off but exploded shortly after in the air after an external rocket came loose and ruptured a fuel tank resulting in the explosion.
The explosion claimed the lives of six astronauts plus a school teacher with millions of people watching on live television across the country.
The teacher, Sharon Crista McAuliffe, a junior high school teacher from Concord, N.H. , was selected to go into space after NASA put out a contest for teachers around the country to become the first private citizen to go into space.
The explosion could have been avoided but a warning light that signaled rising temperatures in the ship making the shuttle vulnerable, was ignored.

On this day in history, January 28, 1986 the Challenger space shuttle was set to lift off but exploded shortly after in the air after an external rocket came loose and ruptured a fuel tank resulting in the explosion.
The explosion claimed the lives of six astronauts plus a school teacher with millions of people watching on live television across the country.
The teacher, Sharon Crista McAuliffe, a junior high school teacher from Concord, N.H. , was selected to go into space after NASA put out a contest for teachers around the country to become the first private citizen to go into space.
The explosion could have been avoided but a warning light that signaled rising temperatures in the ship making the shuttle vulnerable, was ignored.

Now You Know -Largest Playing Card Structure is Taller than a Man

Mark Saxton

A structure replicating three Las Vegas resorts was built of 218,792 playing cards by Brian Berg in Macau, China. It was built in 44 days, being completed on March 10, 2010.

The structure is a replica of The Venetian, The Plaza Macao, and Sands Macao, all located in Las Vegas, Nevada. They stand 34 feet 1.05 inches, 9 feet 5.39 inches, and 11 feet 7.37 inches tall respectively.

The replicas are recognized by Guinness World Records as the tallest card structure in the world.

Brian Berg also holds the world record for the tallest free-standing house of cards, which was 25 feet 9.4375 inches tall. It was attempted at the Texas State Fair on October 16, 2007 in Dallas.

Dumb Criminals- Looking Good My Man!

By Amario May

Police in Lima, Ohio, posted photos of Donald “Chip” Pugh to their
Facebook page, asking for help in locating the fugitive.
Pugh then texted the police a new photo of himself with the message “Here is a better photo that one is terrible.”
Police said Pugh is a person of interest in several cases and his warrant is for his failure to appear as directed in the summons.
Mr. Pugh told an Ohio radio station why he sent the photo, stating "They put a picture out that made me look like I was a Thundercat... or James Brown on the run. I can't do that."

FFA Takes on 212/360 Leadership Conference This Weekend
By Isis Binns

The Southern Cayuga FFA will be commuting to the OnCenter in Syracuse this weekend (January 25 and 26) to attend the 212/360 leadership conference.
This conference is an event for 7-12 grade FFA members to explore and refine their leadership skills with other FFA members from around the area.
The 212 conference focuses mostly on individual leadership skills, which is a good baseline for younger FFA members, which will prepare them for when they are older. They will work on forming positive self images and living healthy lifestyles.
The older members attend the 360 conference, which focuses more on how to use the leadership skills they have acquired through FFA and put them to good use throughout the community. They will work on forming positive relationships and learn how to become more trustworthy individuals.

The Perfect Toy Story

By Amario May

The police are on the lookout for a brazen thief who had broken into a local YMCA in Indio, CA.
The thief had broken into the YMCA through the ceiling in hopes of finding a cash register filled with cash, but neither the cash or register was real.
Security footage of the YMCA shows the man kicking through the duct work of a ceiling in the YMCA child development center in Indio, California. He then drops to the floor in hopes of stealing the money from the cash register, only to later find out that the cash register he robbed and the money taken from it was just a toy.

This Week In History- The Original One Percent
By Zach Lattin

On January 10, 1870, John D. Rockefeller and his brother, Willam Rockefeller, established the Standard Oil Company of Ohio, buying up all the smaller companies and establishing a monopoly over oil.
Rockefeller was born into a large family that was very poor and moved several times for his conman father to avoid the law.
At a young age rockefeller was a salesman of small goods like candy and other sweets to the neighborhood kids to try and bring in some money for his family. This drove Rockefeller to seek ways to achieve his goal of becoming rich and after seeing an oil drill strike oil and throw it into the air he knew how he would.
Rockefeller would become America's first billionaire at the age of 57, even though it's worth about 30 billion in today's money.
Today,over 250 of his direct descendants having a slice of the pie.
